The <b>alheira</b> is a Portuguese sausage made with many meats other than <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../929/19719929.xml">
pork</link>, usually <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../434/32434.xml">
veal</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../674/37674.xml">
duck</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../402/37402.xml">
chicken</link> or <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../573/26573.xml">
rabbit</link>, and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../969/36969.xml">
bread</link>. <p>

It was invented by the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../913/15913.xml">
Jewish</link> as a way to deceive the <message wordnetid="106598915" confidence="0.8">
<subject wordnetid="106599788" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../613/1644613.xml">
Portuguese Inquisition</link></subject>
</message>
. As the Jewish weren't allowed by their religion to eat <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../929/19719929.xml">
pork</link> meat, they were very easily identifiable by the fact that they didn't prepare and smoke the common pork sausages in the smokehouses (or <link>
fumeiros</link>, in Portuguese). They, therefore, replaced <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../929/19719929.xml">
pork</link> meat by a large variety of other meats, such as <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../434/32434.xml">
veal</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../573/26573.xml">
rabbit</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../639/11125639.xml">
turkey</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../674/37674.xml">
duck</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../402/37402.xml">
chicken</link> and sometimes <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../640/63640.xml">
partridge</link>, which would then be mixed with a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../969/36969.xml">
bread</link> dough for consistency. This recipe would spread amongst Christians, although they added the ever-present <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../929/19719929.xml">
pork</link> to it.</p>
<p>

Alheiras are usually fried in olive oil and served with boiled vegetables and potatoes.</p>
<p>

